    <item>
      <title>The smallest piece of lego</title>
      <link>http://vielmetti.github.io/post/2010/2010-04-25-the-smallest-piece-of-lego/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 25 Apr 2010 15:09:27 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://vielmetti.github.io/post/2010/2010-04-25-the-smallest-piece-of-lego/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;is still worth fighting over, if you and your brother both want it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What&#39;s the smallest piece of lego?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.eurobricks.com/forum/index.php?showtopic=35795&amp;pid=625188&amp;mode=threaded&amp;start=&#34;&gt;eurobricks forum&lt;/a&gt; suggests it is a flower petal.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://news.lugnet.com/market/shipping/?n=362&#34;&gt;Lugnut&lt;/a&gt; says a gold coin, weighing in at just over 0.056 g; the flower petal is a hefty 0.064 g.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For reference, a 1x1 plate is 0.176 g and a 1x8 brick is 3.06 g.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&#39;ll need a lot of legos to build a &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.ericharshbarger.org/lego/mosaics.html&#34;&gt;lego mosaic&lt;/a&gt;.  I don&#39;t even want to thing about the cost of lego bricks per kilogram, or maybe I will; this &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.peeron.com/inv/sets/3480-1&#34;&gt;package of 25 1x8 bricks has an MSRP of $6&lt;/a&gt;, or about $80/kg, or $36/lb.  This discussion on &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.classic-space.com/plugins/forum/forum_viewtopic.php?79878&#34;&gt;classic-space&lt;/a&gt; suggests mixed lego goes for $9-12/lb in 2009 dollars.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.lego.com/eng/info/fairplay.asp&#34;&gt;LEGO is a registered trademark owned by the LEGO Group.&lt;/a&gt;  And don&#39;t you forget it.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
